Chapter 12: Introduction to nonlinear learning

12.8 Efficient

In this Section we introduce a second popular, general paradigm for effecient model search. With the first apprach discussed in the previous Section - boosting - we took a 'bottom-up' approach to fine tuning the proper amount of capacity a model needs: we began with a low capacity (and likely underfitting) model, and then gradually increased its capacity by adding additional units (from the samm family of universal approximators) until we achieve a model that minimizes validation error. With the approach we describe in this Section - called regularization - takes the opposite 'top-down' approach. That is, we begin with a high capacity (likely overfitting) model, and then gradually decrease its capacity until we achieve a model that minimizes validation error.

In[1]:

12.8.1 Regularization: the 'top-down' approach

Regularization is the general term given to the method of model search where we begin with a high capacity model - typically consisting of a sum of many feature transformation of the general form

\begin{equation} \text{model}_1\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{w}\right) = w_0 + f_1\left(\mathbf{x}\right){w}_{1} + \cdots + f_B\left(\mathbf{x}\right){w}_{B} \end{equation}

and we gradually decrease its capacity. This can be done in a variety of ways, some of the most popular of which we review here.

It seems intuitive to rank these by one-at-a-time. This does not capture interactions between them - which can be substantial when dealing with deeper neural networks and trees - but nonetheless is an effective tactice.

This is in general done by preventing perfect minimization of a model's associated cost function.

How do you want to adjust things here? Damn - we would need to adjust our model or feature_transforms function.

\begin{equation} g\left(\mathbf{w}\right) = \frac{1}{P}\sum_{p=1}^{P}\text{log}\left(1 + e^{- y_p\text{model}_m\left(\mathbf{x}_p,\mathbf{w}\right)}\right). \end{equation}
\begin{equation} g\left(\mathbf{w}\right) = \frac{1}{P}\sum_{p=1}^{P}\text{log}\left(1 + e^{- y_p\,f_m\left(\mathbf{x}_p\right)w_m -y_p\text{model}_{m-1}\left(\mathbf{x}_p\right)}\right). \end{equation}
\begin{equation} g\left(\mathbf{w}\right) = \frac{1}{P}\sum_{p=1}^{P}\text{log}\left(1 + e^{- y_p\,f_m\left(\mathbf{x}_p\right)w_m}e^{-y_p\text{model}_{m-1}\left(\mathbf{x}_p\right)}\right). \end{equation}
\begin{equation} g\left(\mathbf{w}\right) = \frac{1}{P}\sum_{p=1}^{P}\left(f_m\left(\mathbf{x}_p\right)w_m - \left(y_p - \text{model}_{m-1}\left(\mathbf{x}_p\right)\right)\right)^2. \end{equation}
